579—607. A digression on the rarity of true friendship, and on the many vices of human society.

The latter part of this passage owes something to the conclusion of Catullus’ Peleus and Thetis. Both writers draw their feeling as much frorn the contemplation of Roman society as from Greek legend. The rarity of Fides is a common Stoic theme; cf. Seneca Tranq. An. κν. 1, ed. Hermes, p. 272.
